50|$|When LCD {{shutter glasses}} {{are used for}} stereo 3D displays, the {{effective}} <b>refresh</b> <b>rate</b> is halved, because each eye needs a separate picture. For this reason, it is usually recommended to use a display capable of at least 120 Hz, because divided in half this rate is again 60 Hz. Higher <b>refresh</b> <b>rates</b> result in greater image stability, for example 72 Hz non-stereo is 144 Hz stereo, and 90 Hz non-stereo is 180 Hz stereo. Unfortunately most computer graphics cards and monitors cannot handle these high <b>refresh</b> <b>rates,</b> especially at higher resolutions.|$|R
